questions.explanation:
Cross-account role assumption requires a two-way trust establishment:

**1. Trust Policy in Account B (answer B):**
The SecurityAuditRole must have a trust policy (also called assume role policy) that explicitly allows principals from Account A to assume it. This trust policy might look like:

```json
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Principal": {
      "AWS": "arn:aws:iam::111122223333:user/AuditUser"
    },
    "Action": "sts:AssumeRole"
  }]
}
```

Or more broadly:
```json
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Principal": {
      "AWS": "arn:aws:iam::111122223333:root"
    },
    "Action": "sts:AssumeRole",
    "Condition": {
      "StringEquals": {
        "sts:ExternalId": "unique-external-id-123"
      }
    }
  }]
}
```

**2. Identity-based Policy in Account A (answer C):**
AuditUser must have permissions to call sts:AssumeRole on the specific role ARN:

```json
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Action": "sts:AssumeRole",
    "Resource": "arn:aws:iam::444455556666:role/SecurityAuditRole"
  }]
}
```

**Why both are needed:**
- The trust policy establishes that Account B trusts Account A (Resource-side trust)
- The identity policy grants Account A user permission to assume roles (Identity-side permission)
- Both must be in place for cross-account access to work

**Why other options are incorrect:**
- A: Permissions boundaries limit maximum permissions but don't grant cross-account trust
- D: AWS Organizations and SCPs are not required for cross-account role assumption, though they can provide additional controls

Reference:
- Tutorial: Delegate Access Across AWS Accounts Using IAM Roles: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/tutorial_cross-account-with-roles.html
- How to use trust policies with IAM roles: https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/security/how-to-use-trust-policies-with-iam-roles/
